    {
      "base_language": "Sometimes I read books.",
      "target_language": "가끔 책을 읽어요.",
      "romanized": "Gakkeum chaegeul ilgeoyo.",
      "literal": "Sometimes books read."
    },
    {
      "base_language": "I love watching dramas.",
      "target_language": "드라마 보는 걸 좋아해요.",
      "romanized": "Deurama boneun geol joahaeyo.",
      "literal": "Drama watching thing like.",
      "grammarNote": "〜는 것 (neun geot) nominalizes a verb — turns 'watch' into 'watching': 보는 것/걸 (the thing of watching). 좋아하다 (joahada) = 'to like'. So 드라마 보는 걸 좋아해요 = 'I like watching dramas'. This nominalizer pattern is very common in Korean."
    },
    {
      "base_language": "What drama are you watching these days?",
      "target_language": "요즘 무슨 드라마 봐요?",
      "romanized": "Yojeum museun deurama bwayo?",
      "literal": "These-days what drama watching?",
      "grammarNote": "요즘 무슨 드라마 봐요? is one of the most natural conversation starters in Korea — K-dramas are a central part of social culture. 무슨 (museun) = 'what kind of / which' when asking about unspecified things."
    },
